      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Detecting an ARP spoofing attack can be a bit tricky, but there are ways to spot it. One method is to monitor ARP traffic on the network. You can use tools like Wireshark to capture and analyze the packets. If you see multiple devices responding to the same IP address with different MAC addresses, that's a red flag. It's like noticing that everyone in the cafe is using the same lunch money but different names.\n\nAnother way to detect ARP spoofing is to use static ARP entries. This means you manually assign IP addresses to MAC addresses on your device, so it doesn't accept new ARP responses. It's like having a list of trusted friends you only give your lunch money to.\n\nHowever, these methods might not always be practical, especially if you're just hanging out at a cafe. The best way to protect yourself is to use a VPN, which encrypts your data and makes it harder for an attacker to intercept it. It's like having a secret code that only you and the website you're connecting to understand.",
